defaultSuggested improvements:
defaultBackground from Community Action defaultSurrey who have supported voluntary car schemes for over 20 yearsdefault“
defaultIn Surrey voluntary car schemes/good neighbo
defaultu
defaultr schemes have existed for almost 50 years and Surrey CA has supported these for over 20 years.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe have about 100 such schemes offering transport to anyone in their communities but it is almost all elderly people who use the service.
default&#xa0;
default The schemes vary in size from 10 volunteers to 150 volunteers, doing as few as 120 passenger journeys to 15,000 passe
defaultnger journeys a year. Last year we did a short survey of the schemes and we had a 79% return rate. The 79% reported that they did 82,500 passenger journeys for 7,300 clients.
default&#xa0;
default Our estimate is that approximately 75% would have been health related journeys.
default&#xa0;
default Of all the requests only 0.7% w
defaultere
default turned down and that was usually because too short notice was given.
default&#xa0;
defaultThese voluntary schemes work very well in the communities that have them.
default&#xa0;
default The Voluntary Car Schemes Adviser is continually trying to develop new sche
defaultmes.
default&#xa0;
default In the past 
default21
default years Surrey Community Action has assisted 43 schemes to develop.
default&#xa0;
default There are another three in the pipeline and another two possible new schemes.
default&#xa0;
defaultOn the evidence to date, it would seem that until every community/village/town has such a 
defaultscheme, this development work will continue as there does appear to be a need for the schemes across the county, both in urban and rural areas. 
default&#xa0;
defaultClients find these schemes to be a lifeline for them.
default&#xa0;
default The schemes provide transport to hospital appointments 
defaultbefore hospital transport even begins work.
default&#xa0;
default They will go across borders and the drivers wait for their clients, often st
defaultaying with them in the hospital”
